### **Products**

1. Filter out the historical data

As set before, no historical data needs to be held, therefore, I'll start by querying:

```SQL
SELECT
prd_id,
cat_id,
prd_key,
prd_nm,
prd_cost,
prd_line,
prd_start_dt
FROM silver.crm_prd_info
WHERE prd_end_dt IS NULL;
```

This is because on the silver layer, I set the end date of the most recent information of the product to **NULL**, meaning that it's still the ongoing information about this product.

2. Joining the other product tables, reordering column order and renaming them to reader and analytics friendly names:

```SQL
SELECT
pn.prd_id AS product_id,
pn.prd_key AS product_number,
pn.prd_nm AS product_name,
pn.cat_id AS category_id,
pc.cat AS category,
pc.subcat AS subcategory,
pc.maintenance AS maintenance,
pn.prd_cost AS product_cost,
pn.prd_line AS product_line,
pn.prd_start_dt AS product_start_date
FROM silver.crm_prd_info pn
LEFT JOIN silver.erp_px_cat_g1v2 pc
ON pn.cat_id = pc.id
WHERE prd_end_dt IS NULL;
```

3. Plan on how to fit it into the Star Schema and Create the view.

Once again this table has a lot of descriptive information, this time about the products, so it will be a dimension table. For this, I'll create a surrogate key also for the product's dimension table, as well as create the VIEW with the following query:

```SQL
CREATE VIEW gold.dim_products AS
SELECT
ROW_NUMBER() OVER (ORDER BY pn.prd_start_dt, pn.prd_key) AS product_key,
pn.prd_id AS product_id,
pn.prd_key AS product_number,
pn.prd_nm AS product_name,
pn.cat_id AS category_id,
pc.cat AS category,
pc.subcat AS subcategory,
pc.maintenance AS maintenance,
pn.prd_cost AS product_cost,
pn.prd_line AS product_line,
pn.prd_start_dt AS product_start_date
FROM silver.crm_prd_info pn
LEFT JOIN silver.erp_px_cat_g1v2 pc
ON pn.cat_id = pc.id
WHERE prd_end_dt IS NULL;
```

